The Nigerian bourse yesterday closed lower to  reverse the previous day’s gain as bears regained grip following sell-off that had persisted on the equities market. Market breadth closed negative as GSK led 14 gainers as against 11 losers at the end of the trading session. Consequently, the All-Share Index dipped 81.28 basis points or 0.30 per cent to close at 26,584.45 index points as against 26.665.73 recorded the previous trading session while market capitalisation of equities depreciated by N38 billion from N12.870 trillion the previous session to N12.832 trillion as market sentiment remained on the negative territory Meanwhile, a turnover of 304.2 million shares exchanged in 2,690 deals was recorded in the day’s trading. The premium sub-sector was the most active (measured by turnover volume); with 195.7 million shares exchanged by investors in 1,023 deals. Volume in the sub-sector was largely driven by activities in the shares of Zenith Bank Plc and Access Bank Plc. Also, the banking sub-sector boosted by activities in shares of Ecobank Plc and GTBank Plc followed with a turnover of 39.6 million shares in 405 deals. Further analysis of the day’s trading showed that in percentage terms, GSK  Plc topped the day’s gainers’ table with 9.52 per cent to close at N5.75 per share while AG Leventis Plc followed with 8.70 per cent to close at 50 kobo per share. Wema Bank Plc added 7.14 per cent to close at 75 kobo per share. On the flip side, Cornerstone Insurance Plc led the losers with a drop of 9.80 per cent to close at 46 kobo per share while UPD Credit  Plc shed 9.59 per cent to close at N23.30 per share. UAC Property Plc trailed with 6.67 per cent to close at 84 kobo per share.